metadata.name: Tangled #2
metadata.description:
"Tangled" is a generative art project that explores the emergent behaviour of simple shapes moving according to a random flow field. While the final result is always constrained to the shape of a circle, the variation within is endless.

Instructions:
Press "p" to pause the animation.
In live mode, press 1 through 5 to save a PNG version of the final result. The following resolutions are available:
1: 400 x 400 (ideal for Twitter PFP)
2: 1000 x 1000
3: 2000 x 2000
4: 4000 x 4000
5: 5000 x 5000
Please be patient, generating the PNG may take some time!

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Dazicker 50/50 #34
metadata.description:
Stickers are a universal form of expression, with Dazicker 50/50 the fragile paper sticker meets the digital dazzle pattern.

50/50
top/bottom
cut-away/remain

Dazicker 50/50, slices into a sticker, removing a dazzle camo pattern. Like a stencil in reverse. We are creating a new item from digital destruction.

You may rarely get a complete sticker with no patterns cut into it.

S to download in hi=rez

metadata.name: Lines and Planes #67
metadata.description:
A series of lines and planes intersect at random angles in varying densities and color schemes to create an ever changing composition. Each iteration is unique. Rarity features work as follows :
1. Black backgrounds are common, white - less common and red - very rare.
2. Density of lines and planes are less common with increase in density.
3. Angle distribution are almost uniformly distributed.

metadata.name: Fizz 2.0 #32
metadata.description:
Experimental Art.

This piece is inspired by a mathematical theorem known as 'Circle packing'. This algorithm aims to cram a bunch of circles into space as tightly as possible. This is a well-explored topic throughout the history of mathematics, but at the end of the day it's mathematics, it's BORING. So to make 'Fizz' a little bit thrilling and different, I wrote an algorithm that randomly draws 450 circles with totally different radiuses (range(width * 0.1, width * 0.001) to be exact) on a canvas, and checks each circle, if the randomly chosen location is a good fit for a new circle to avoid collisions.

Combined with some cool colors and gradients for both the background and the circles, this procedure is all it took to produce 'Fizz'.
Bereft of meaning, feel free to interpret it as you please.
